ğŸ” Exploitation Process (Step-by-Step)
Step 1: Attempt Normal Purchase

Logged in as user: student

Account balance: $0.00

Attempted to add expensive items to the cart

The application blocked the action using client-side validation

Step 2: Intercept â€œAdd to Cartâ€ Request

When clicking Add to Cart, Burp intercepted a request similar to:

POST /add-to-cart HTTP/1.1
Host: localhost
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded

product_id=5&price=1500&quantity=1

Step 3: Modify Request Parameters

The request was edited directly inside Burp:

Original:
product_id=5&price=1500&quantity=1

Modified:
product_id=5&price=1&quantity=1

Step 4: Forward the Request

After modification, the Forward button was clicked.

âœ… The item successfully appeared in the shopping cart
âœ… The server accepted the manipulated price
âœ… Client-side controls were bypassed

ğŸ§  Key Discoveries

Client-side validation can be bypassed easily

Burp Suite allows full visibility and modification of web traffic

Servers that trust client input are vulnerable

Prices, balances, and permissions should never be enforced on the client

ğŸ“š What I Learned

How proxies work in web security testing

How HTTP requests are structured (headers + body)

How attackers manipulate POST and GET parameters

Why HTTPS does not protect against logic flaws

The importance of server-side validation

ğŸš¨ Real-World Attacker Use

In real applications, attackers can use this technique to:

Purchase items for free

Bypass payment checks

Manipulate account balances

Exploit discount and coupon systems

Commit financial fraud

This exact vulnerability has caused real financial losses in production systems.

ğŸ” How Applications Can Be Secured

To prevent this attack:

âœ… Enforce server-side validation

âœ… Never trust client-sent values (price, role, balance)

âœ… Recalculate prices on the server

âœ… Use integrity checks or server-side sessions

âœ… Log and monitor suspicious request manipulation

